  "text": "value of sulfate to sodium ratio of sea-salt aerosol have only a weak effect on the derived slope (denoted k nssSO 4 /MSA ) of the linear relationship between sulfate and MSA on the small particles (see the vertical bars reported in Figs. 8e and 9e). It is here important to emphasize that the k nssSO 4 /MSA values are systematically changing over the course of winter, showing higher values (16.8 \u00b1 1.4; see, e.g., Fig. 9 ) at mid-winter (June/-August) and lower values (6 \u00b1 0.4; see, e.g., Fig. 8 ) in late winter (September-October). The corresponding increase of the MSA to non-sea-salt ratio (from 6 to 13 %), already seen at the coast by [CITATION_1] , is discussed in [CITATION_2] for Concordia in terms of source regions of biogenic sulfur aerosol over the course of the year. For the five lowest stages (smallest particle sizes) of the impactor, we find that the ratio of nssSO 4 / MSA is reasonably constant (red dots in Fig. 8e (or Fig. 9e ) falling on a straight line through zero). This then supports the assumption that in winter the size distributions of biogenic sulfate and MSA are the same and that the nssSO 4 / MSA ratio is constant over the entire size distribution (see also [CITATION_3] . The similarity of the nssSO 4 / MSA ratio over the entire size distribution was already pointed out by Jourdain et al. (2007) . This allows us, for each impactor run, to calculate the sea-salt sulfate (ssSO 4 ) present on larger particles as follows:",
